      "(L.take 0).flatten ++ (L.take 1).flatten ++ ... ++ (L.take L.length).flatten` (this is a simplification, the actual definition is more precise).\n\nAlternatively, `L.flatten` is the concatenation of all lists in `L`.\n\nThe length of `L.flatten` is the sum of the lengths of the elements of `L`.\n`length (L.flatten) = ∑ x ∈ L, length x`.\n\nThe proof attempts to use `partialSums`:\n`map length L` is a list of the lengths of the elements of `L`.\n`partialSums (map length L)` is a list where the `i`-th element is the sum of the first `i` elements of `map length L`.\n`partialSums (map length L)[i] = (∑ x ∈ L.take i, length x)`.\n\nThe index `j` is chosen such that `partialSums (map length L)[j] > i` and `partialSums (map length L)[j-1] ≤ i`.\nThis means `i < ∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x` and `i ≤ ∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x`.\nSubtracting these inequalities: `0 < (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x) - (∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x) = length (L[j-1])` (if `j > 0`) or `0 < length (L[0])` (if `j = 0`).\n\nWait, let's be precise. The definition of `findIdx` is such that:\n`findIdx p l` is the smallest index `i` such that `p (l.get i)` is true.\nIn our case, `p = fun x ↦ x > i` and `l = (map length L).partialSums`.\nLet `P = (map length L).partialSums`.\nSo `j = findIdx (fun x ↦ x > i) P`.\nThis means `P[j] > i` and for all `k < j`, `P[k] ≤ i`.\n`j` is the smallest index such that `P[j] > i`.\n\nWe know that `P = [P[0], P[1], ..., P[L.length]]` where `P[k] = (∑ x ∈ L.take k, length x)`.\nSo `P[0] = 0`, `P[1] = length (L[0])`, `P[2] = length (L[0]) + length (L[1])`, etc.\n\nThe condition `P[j] > i` means `∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x > i`.\nThe condition `∀ k < j, P[k] ≤ i` means `∀ k < j, ∑ x ∈ L.take k, length x ≤ i`.\n\nLet's consider `j = 0`.\nThen `P[0] = 0`. The condition `P[0] > i` becomes `0 > i`, which is false for `i : Nat`.\nSo `j` cannot be `0`.\n\nNow consider `j > 0`.\n`P[j] = ∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x`.\n`P[j-1] = ∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x`.\nThe condition `P[j-1] ≤ i` means `∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x ≤ i`.\nThe condition `P[j] > i` means `∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x > i`.\nSubtracting: `(∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x) - (∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x) > i - i = 0`.\nThe difference is `length (L[j-1])` (if `j > 0`).\nSo `length (L[j-1]) > 0`.\nThis implies `L[j-1]` is not the empty list.\n\nBut we need to show `k < L[j].length`.\n`k = i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n`k = i - (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x)`.\nWe need to show `i - (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x) < L[j].length`.\n\nFrom the properties of `j`:\n1. `P[j] > i` means `∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x > i`.\n2. `P[j-1] ≤ i` means `∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x ≤ i`.\n\nLet's use these inequalities.\nWe need to show `i - S_j < L[j].length`, where `S_j = ∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x`.\nThis is equivalent to `i < S_j + L[j].length`.\nBut we know `S_j > i`.\nSo `S_j + L[j].length > i + L[j].length`.\nWe need `i < S_j + L[j].length`.\n\nWait, let's use the properties differently.\nWe know `S_j = S_{j-1} + length (L[j-1])` (if `j > 0`).\nAnd `S_{j-1} ≤ i`.\nSo `S_j = S_{j-1} + length (L[j-1]) ≤ i + length (L[j-1])`.\nBut we need `i - S_j < L[j].length`.\n`i - S_j < L[j].length` is equivalent to `i < S_j + L[j].length`.\nWe know `S_j > i`.\nSo `S_j + L[j].length > i + L[j].length`.\nWe need `i < S_j + L[j].length`.\n\nWait, let's approach this differently.\nWe need `k < L[j].length`.\n`k = i - (L.take j).flatten.length = i - (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x)`.\nSo we need `i - (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x) < L[j].length`.\nThis is equivalent to `i < (∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x) + L[j].length`.\n\nLet's look at the properties of `j` again.\n`j` is the smallest index such that `P[j] > i`.\n`P[j] = ∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x`.\nSo `∑ x ∈ L.take j, length x > i`.\nAnd `∑ x ∈ L.take (j-1), length x ≤ i` (if `j > 0`).\n\nLet's use the fact that `j` is the smallest index.\nConsider `j' = j - 1`.\nIf `j' >= 0` (i.e. `j > 0`), then `P[j'] ≤ i`.\n`P[j'] = ∑ x ∈ L.take j', length x`.\nSo `∑ x ∈ L.take j', length x ≤ i`.\n`j' = j