      "by\n```\n\nNow we need to prove `k < L[j].length`. Let's expand the definitions and use reasoning.\n\n```tactics\n  have h1 : (L.map length).partialSums[j] > i := by\n    have h2 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums ≤ (L.map length).partialSums.length := by\n      apply findIdx_le\n    have h3 : (L.map length).partialSums[j] > i := by\n      have h4 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1] > i := by\n        have h5 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums > 0 := by\n          by_contra h6\n          push_neg at h6\n          have h7 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums = 0 := by\n            omega\n          rw [h7] at h2\n          simp at h2\n          all_goals\n            try { tauto }\n          all_goals\n            try { nlinarith }\n        have h8 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1] > i := by\n          have h9 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1] > i := by\n            have h10 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums > 0 := h5\n            have h11 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1] > i := by\n              apply (List.getElem_lt_iff (by\n                have h12 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums > 0 := h5\n                omega\n              )).mpr\n              simp [findIdx]\n            assumption\n          assumption\n        assumption\n      have h4' : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1 = j := by\n        omega\n      rw [h4'] at h4\n      linarith\n    assumption\n```\n\nWait, this is getting complicated. Let's use a more direct approach. The definition of `j` is `(L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1`. Let's denote `f = fun x => decide (x > i)`. Then `j` is the index such that `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i` and `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i` (if `j+1 < length`).\n\nBut in Lean's `List.findIdx`, it's defined as the smallest index `i` such that `p l[i]` is true. So `findIdx p l` is the smallest index `i` such that `p l[i]` is true. So `(L.map length).partialSums[findIdx f (map length L).partialSums]` is the first element in `partialSums` that is greater than `i`.\n\nTherefore, `(L.map length).partialSums[findIdx f (map length L).partialSums - 1]` is the last element in `partialSums` that is less than or equal to `i`. So `(L.map length).partialSums[j]` is the first element greater than `i`.\n\nTherefore, `h1` states that `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`.\n\nNow, we need to relate this to `k < L[j].length`.\n\nWe know that `(L.map length).partialSums[j]` is the sum of lengths of the first `j` elements of `L`. So `(L.map length).partialSums[j] = (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nAlso, `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1]` is the sum of lengths of the first `j+1` elements. So `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] = (take (j+1) L).flatten.length`.\n\nSince `j` is the index of the first element in `partialSums` greater than `i`, we have `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i` and `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i` (if `j+1 < length`).\n\nSo we have:\n- `(take j L).flatten.length = (L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`\n- `(take (j+1) L).flatten.length = (L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i` (if `j+1 < length`)\n\nBut `(take (j+1) L).flatten.length = (take j L).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\n\nSo from `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i`, we have `(take j L).flatten.length + L[j].length ≤ i`.\n\nTherefore, `L[j].length ≤ i - (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nBut we need to show `k < L[j].length`, which is `i - (take j L).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\n\nFrom `L[j].length ≤ i - (take j L).flatten.length`, we can't directly conclude the strict inequality. However, we know that `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`. This means that `(take j L).flatten.length > i`.\n\nWait, no. `(L.map length).partialSums[j]` is the sum of the first `j` elements' lengths. So `(L.map length).partialSums[j] = (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nTherefore, `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i` means `(take j L).flatten.length > i`.\n\nBut then `k = i - (take j L).flatten.length`. If `(take j L).flatten.length > i`, then `k` would be negative. But in Lean, subtraction of natural numbers is defined such that if `a < b`, then `a - b = 0`.\n\nWait, this is a problem. If `(take j L).flatten.length > i`, then `k = i - (take j L).flatten.length = 0`.\n\nSo the goal becomes `0 < L[j].length`. Is this true?\n\nWe know that `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`. This is `(take j L).flatten.length > i`.\n\nAlso, `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1]` is the sum of the first `j+1` elements' lengths. This is `(take (j+1) L).flatten.length`.\n\nSince `j` is the index of the first element in `partialSums` greater than `i`, we have `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i` and `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i` (if `j+1 < length`).\n\nBut `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] = (L.map length).partialSums[j] + L[j].length`.\n\nSo `L[j].length = (L.map length).partialSums[j+1] - (L.map length).partialSums[j]`.\n\nSince `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1] ≤ i` and `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`, we have `L[j].length ≤ i - (L.map length).partialSums[j]`.\n\nBut `(L.map length).partialSums[j] = (take j L).flatten.length`. So `L[j].length ≤ i - (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nThe goal is `k < L[j].length`, which is `i - (take j L).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\n\nFrom `L[j].length ≤ i - (take j L).flatten.length`, we can't directly conclude the strict inequality. However, we know that `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i`. This means that `(take j L).flatten.length > i`.\n\nBut if `(take j L).flatten.length > i`, then `k = i - (take j L).flatten.length = 0` (in Lean's natural number subtraction). So the goal becomes `0 < L[j].len