ave `h17 : findIdx ... ≤ (L.map length).partialSums.length`.\nAnd `h16 : findIdx ... > 0`.\nSo `findIdx ... ≥ 1`.\nAnd `findIdx ... ≤ L.length + 1`.\nSo `j = findIdx ... - 1 ≤ L.length`.\nThis is consistent with `hj`.\n\nLet's continue:\n\n```tactics\n        interval_cases h : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums <;> omega\n```\n\nThis is getting too complex. Let's use the fact that `j` is the index such that the sum of lengths up to `j` is the first sum that exceeds `i`.\nThis means:\n- `(L.take j).flatten.length ≤ i`\n- `i < (L.take (j+1)).flatten.length` (which is `(L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`)\n\nThese are the properties we need.\nLet's use them directly:\n\n```tactics\n      simpa using h12\n    simpa using h8\n```\n\nSo we have `h6 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i))] > i`.\nThis means `(L.take (findIdx ...)).flatten.length > i`.\nAnd `(L.take (findIdx ...)).flatten.length = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nSo `i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nThis implies `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  have h7 : (L.take j).flatten.length ≤ i := by\n    have h8 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1] ≤ i := h5\n    have h9 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1] = (L.take j).flatten.length := by\n      simp [j]\n      <;> try { tauto }\n      <;> try { linarith }\n```\n\nSo we have `h9 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx ... - 1] = (L.take j).flatten.length`.\nAnd `h8 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx ... - 1] ≤ i`.\nSo `(L.take j).flatten.length ≤ i`.\nThis is what we need.\n\nLet's continue:\n\n```tactics\n    linarith\n```\n\nSo we have `h7 : (L.take j).flatten.length ≤ i`.\nNow we need to show `i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nThis is `i < (L.take (j+1)).flatten.length`.\nAnd we know that `findIdx (fun x => x > i) (map length L).partialSums` is the smallest index `k` such that `(map length L).partialSums[k] > i`.\nSo `(map length L).partialSums[findIdx ...] > i`.\nAnd `(map length L).partialSums[findIdx ...] = (L.take (findIdx ...)).flatten.length`.\nSo `(L.take (findIdx ...)).flatten.length > i`.\nAnd `L[j].length` is part of this sum.\nSo `(L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length > i`.\nThis means `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  have h8 : i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length := by\n    have h9 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i))] > i := h6\n    have h10 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i))] = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length := by\n      simp [j]\n      <;> try { tauto }\n      <;> try { linarith }\n```\n\nSo we have `h10 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx ...] = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nAnd `h9 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx ...] > i`.\nSo `(L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length > i`.\nThis is what we need.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n    linarith\n```\n\nSo we have `h8 : i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nThis means `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\nThis is the goal.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  have h9 : k < L[j].length := by\n    omega\n```\n\nSo the goal is proved.\nThe key insight is that `j` is chosen such that `j` is the index of the list in `L` that contains the i-th element of `L.flatten`. This means that the sum of lengths of the first `j` lists is less than or equal to `i`, and the sum of lengths of the first `j+1` lists is greater than or equal to `i`.\nSpecifically, `findIdx (fun x => x > i) (map length L).partialSums` gives the index `k0` such that the sum of lengths up to `k0` is the first sum that exceeds `i`. This means:\n- `(L.take k0).flatten.length > i`\n- `(L.take (k0-1)).flatten.length ≤ i`\nSo if `j = k0 - 1`, then `(L.take j).flatten.length ≤ i`.\nAnd `L[j].length` is part of the sum `(L.take (k0)).flatten.length`.\nSo `L[j].length > 0`.\nAnd `i < (L.take (k0)).flatten.length = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nThis implies `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\n\nThe Lean proof effectively uses the properties of `findIdx` to establish these inequalities.\n</think>\n```lean\nimport Mathlib\n\ntheorem getElem_flatten_aux₂ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : i < L.flatten.length) :\n    let j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1;\n    have hj := @List.getElem_flatten_aux₁ α L i h;\n    let k := i - (L.take j).flatten.length;\n    k < L[j].length := by\n  have h1 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums ≤ (L.map length).partialSums.length := by\n    apply findIdx_le\n  have h2 : (L.map length).partialSums.length = L.length + 1 := by\n    simp [length_partialSums]\n  have h3 : (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) > 0 := by\n    by_contra h\n    push_neg at h\n    have h4 : (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) = 0 := by\n      omega\n    have h5 : (L.map length).partialSums[0] > i := by\n      have h6 : (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) = 0 := h4\n      rw [findIdx_eq_zero] at h6\n      all_goals\n        try { tauto }\n        try { linarith }\n    have h6 : (L.map length).partialSums[0] = 0 := by\n      simp [partialSums]\n    omega\n  have h4 : (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) ≤ L.length + 1 := by\n    have h5 : (L.map length).partialSums.length = L.length + 1 := by\n      simp [length_partialSums]\n    have h6 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums ≤ (L.map length).partialSums.length := by\n      apply findIdx_le\n    rw [h5] at h6\n    omega\n  have h5 : (L.map length).partialSums[findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1] ≤ i := by\n    have h6 : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums > 0 := h3\n    have h7 : ∀ k < findIdx (fun