      "i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n   - From the definition of `j`, we know that `(map length L).partialSums[j] > i`. The partial sums list is `S = [s_0, s_1, ..., s_n]` where `s_i = sum_{k=0}^i length(L[k])`. So `S[j] > i`.\n   - The value `S[j]` is the sum of lengths up to index `j-1` (if we use 0-based indexing for the partial sums list). Let's clarify the indexing.\n   - Let `S = (map length L).partialSums`. `S` has length `L.length`. `S[i] = sum_{j=0}^i length(L[j])`.\n   - `findIdx (fun x => x > i) S` gives the index `a` such that `S[a] > i` and `S[b] > i` for all `b < a`. The definition uses `decide` which is `if x > i then true else false`.\n   - So `a` is the smallest index such that `S[a] > i`. Then `j = a - 1`.\n   - This means `S[j+1] > i`.\n   - `S[j+1] = sum_{k=0}^{j+1} length(L[k])`.\n   - `S[j] = sum_{k=0}^j length(L[k])`.\n   - We need to show `k < L[j].length`.\n   - `k = i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n   - `(L.take j).flatten.length = sum_{k=0}^{j-1} length(L[k])` (if `j > 0`). Let's be precise.\n   - `(L.take j).flatten.length = S[j]` (if `j > 0`). Let's confirm.\n   - Yes, `S[j] = sum_{k=0}^{j-1} length(L[k])` if we use the standard definition of `partialSums`. Let's check the Lean definition.\n   - The Lean definition of `partialSums` is `List.foldr List.append []`. So `partialSums [a,b,c] = [a, a+b, a+b+c]`. So `partialSums L` has length `L.length + 1`.\n   - Let `S = (map length L).partialSums`. `S` has length `L.length + 1`.\n   - `S[0] = 0` (if we use the standard `partialSums` definition which starts with 0).\n   - `S[i] = sum_{j=0}^{i-1} length(L[j])` for `i > 0`.\n   - Let's use the standard definition. `S[0] = 0`. `S[i] = sum_{j=0}^{i-1} length(L[j])` for `i > 0`.\n   - `findIdx (fun x => x > i) S` gives the smallest index `a` such that `S[a] > i`. Then `j = a - 1`.\n   - So `S[j+1] > i`.\n   - `S[j+1] = sum_{k=0}^j length(L[k])`.\n   - We need to show `k < L[j].length`.\n   - `k = i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n   - `(L.take j