      " L).flatten.length\n    k < L[j].length := sorry\n```\n\nThe theorem aims to prove `k < L[j].length`, where:\n- `j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1`\n- `hj : j < L.length` (derived from `getElem_flatten_aux₁`)\n- `k := i - (take j L).flatten.length`\n\nTo prove `k < L[j].length`, we need to show `i - (take j L).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\nThis is equivalent to `i < L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nWe know:\n1. `j < L.length` (from `hj`)\n2. `i < L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length` (we need to show this)\n\nLet's think about the relationship between the total length of the flattened list and the individual parts.\n\nThe total length of the flattened list is `L.flatten.length`.\nThe length of the `j`-th list is `L[j].length`.\nThe sum of the lengths of the first `j` lists is `(L.take j).flatten.length`.\n\nFrom the properties of `List.flatten` and `List.length`, we have:\n`L.flatten.length = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length + (L.drop (j+1)).flatten.length`.\n\nHowever, we need to show `i < L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nWe know `i < L.flatten.length`.\nSo we need to show `L.flatten.length ≤ L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nLet's look at the structure of `L.flatten`:\n`L.flatten = L[0] ++ L[1] ++ ... ++ L[n-1]` (if `L = [L0, L1, ..., Ln-1]`)\n\nSo, `L[j].length` is the length of one part, and `(take j L).flatten.length` is the sum of the lengths of the first `j` parts.\n\nTherefore, `L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length = L[j].length + (L[0].length + ... + L[j-1].length)`.\n\nWe know `L.flatten.length = (L[0].length + ... + L[j-1].length) + L[j].length + (L[j+1].length + ... + L[n-1].length)`.\n\nSo, `L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length = L[j].length + (L[0].length + ... + L[j-1].length)`.\nAnd `L.flatten.length = (L[0].length + ... + L[j-1].length) + L[j].length + (L[j+1].length + ... + L[n-1].length)`.\n\nTherefore, `L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length ≤ L.flatten.length`.\n\nSince we have `i < L.flatten.length`, it follows that `i ≤ L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nBut we need `i < L[j].length + (take j L).flatten.length`.\n\nWait, this suggests that we might need more information or a different approach.\n\nLet's re-think: We need to show `k < L[j].length`, which is `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\nThis is equivalent to `i < L[j].length + (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n\nWe know:\n- `i < L.flatten.length`\n- `L.flatten.length = (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length + (L.drop (j+1)).flatten.length`\n\nSo `i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length + (L.drop (j+1)).flatten.length`.\n\nSince `(L.drop (j+1)).flatten.length ≥ 0`, we have `i ≤ (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\nBut we need `i < (L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`.\n\nThis suggests that we might need to use properties of `findIdx` more carefully.\n\nThe definition of `findIdx` is `List.findIdx p l = match l with | [] => 0 | x :: xs => if p x then 0 else 1 + findIdx p xs`.\n\nSo `j = findIdx (fun x => x > i) (map length L).partialSums - 1`.\n\nLet's think about what `j` represents. `j` is one less than the index of the first element in `(map length L).partialSums` that is greater than `i`. This corresponds to the sum of lengths of the first `j+1` lists.\n\nWait, `(map length L).partialSums` is the list of partial sums of lengths. The `j`-th element of this list is the sum of lengths of the first `j` lists.\n\nSo, `j` is the largest index such that the sum of lengths of the first `j` lists is ≤ `i`. Specifically, `j` is such that:\n- `(map length L).partialSums[j] ≤ i`\n- `(map length L).partialSums[j+1] > i` (if `j+1 < L.length`)\n\nTherefore, `j` is the largest index such that `sum_{k=0}^{j-1} L[k].length ≤ i`.\nThen `j` is such that `sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length > i`.\n\nBut we need to show `i < L[j].length + sum_{k=0}^{j-1} L[k].length`.\nThis is exactly `i < sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length`.\n\nBut by the definition of `j`, we know `sum_{k=0}^{j-1} L[k].length ≤ i` (if `j > 0`).\nAnd `sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length > i`.\n\nSo we need to show `i < sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length`. This is exactly what the definition of `j` gives us.\n\nTo prove this in Lean, we need to relate `j` back to the properties of `findIdx`.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n\ntheorem getElem_flatten_aux₂ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : i < L.flatten.length) :\n    let j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) - 1\n    have hj : j < L.length := getElem_flatten_aux₁ L i h\n    let k := i - (take j L).flatten.length\n    k < L[j].length := sorry\n```\n\nThe proof needs to be completed. Let's think about how to complete it.\n\nWe need to show `k < L[j].length`, which is `i - (L.take j).flatten.length < L[j].length`.\nThis is equivalent to `i < L[j].length + (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n\nWe know:\n1. `j < L.length` (from `hj`)\n2. `i < L.flatten.length` (from `h`)\n3. `j = findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums - 1`\n\nLet's think about the properties of `findIdx`.\n`findIdx p l` gives the index of the first element in `l` that satisfies `p`. If all elements satisfy `p`, it returns `0`. If none satisfy `p`, it returns `length l`.\n\nSo, `j + 1 = findIdx (fun x => x > i) (map length L).partialSums`.\nThis means:\n- If `j+1 < L.length`, then `(map length L).partialSums[j+1] > i`.\n- If `j+1 = L.length`, then all elements of `(map length L).partialSums` are ≤ `i`.\n\nAlso, by the definition of `findIdx`, we have that `(map length L).partialSums[j] ≤ i` if `j < L.length`.\n\nSo, we know that `sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length > i`.\nBut `L[j].length + (L.take j).flatten.length = sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length`.\n\nTherefore, we need to show `i < sum_{k=0}^{j} L[k].length`.\n\nThis is exactly what the properties of `findIdx` give us.\n\nTo complete the proof in Lean, we need to formalize this reasoning.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n\ntheorem getElem_flatten_aux₂ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : 