Let's think about how to prove this. We need to relate `k` to the length of `L[j]`.

From the definition of `j`:
*   `j` is the index of the sublist `L[j]` that contains the `i`-th element of `L.flatten`.
*   This means `(L.map length).partialSums[j] > i` and `(L.map length).partialSums[j-1] ≤ i` (if `j > 0`).
*   The length of `L[j]` is `(L.map length).partialSums[j] - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1]` (or `L[j].length` if `j=0`).

From the definition of `k`:
*   `k = i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.
*   `(L.take j).flatten.length` is the sum of lengths of `L[0], L[1], ..., L[j-1]`.
*   So, `k = i - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1]` (if `j > 0`) or `k = i` (if `j = 0`).

To prove `k < L[j].length`:
*   If `j = 0`: `k = i`, and we need `i < L[0].length`. Since `L[0].length = (L.map length).partialSums[0]`, and `i < (L.map length).partialSums[0]` (because `j=0` is the first index where the condition is true), this holds.
*   If `j > 0`: `k = i - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1]`. We need `i - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1] < L[j].length`. Since `L[j].length = (L.map length).partialSums[j] - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1]`, we need `i - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1] < (L.map length).partialSums[j] - (L.map length).partialSums[j-1]`, which simplifies to `i < (L.map length).partialSums[j]`, which is true by the definition of `j`.

